'''Wells Cathedral''' is a [[Church of England]] place of worship in [[Wells, Somerset|Wells]], [[Somerset]] dedicated to [[St Andrew the Apostle]], and is the seat of the [[Bishop of Bath and Wells]]. As with other [[cathedral]]s, it is the central church of a [[Diocese of Bath and Wells|diocese]] and contains the bishop's throne ([[cathedra]]).  The present building dates from 1175 to 1490, an earlier church having been built on the site in 705. It is moderately sized among the [[Architecture of the medieval cathedrals of England|medieval cathedrals of England]], falling between those of massive proportion, such as [[Lincoln Cathedral|Lincoln]] and [[York Minster|York]], and the much smaller cathedrals of [[Christ Church Cathedral, Oxford|Oxford]] and [[Carlisle Cathedral|Carlisle]]. With its broad west front and large central tower, it is the dominant feature of its small [[City status in the United Kingdom|cathedral city]] and a landmark in the Somerset countryside.{{sfn|Swaan|1984|pp=188<U+2013>196}} Wells has been variously described as "unquestionably one of the most beautiful"<ref>Oggins, Robin. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=DtS2iD79NgEC&pg=PA42 Cathedrals]'', p. 42 (Sterling Publishing Company 1996).</ref> and as "the most poetic" of English cathedrals.{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=274}}

The architecture of the cathedral presents a harmonious whole which is entirely [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] and mostly in a single style, the [[Early English Gothic]] of the late 12th and early 13th centuries. In this Wells differs from most other English medieval cathedrals, which have parts in the earlier [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] architectural style introduced to Britain by the [[Normans]] in the 11th century.

Work on the cathedral commenced in about 1175 at the eastern end with the building of the [[Choir (architecture)|choir]]. The historian [[John Harvey (historian)|John Harvey]] considers this to be the first truly Gothic structure in Europe, having broken from the last constraints of Romanesque.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=19}} The stonework of its pointed [[arcade (architecture)|arcade]]s and fluted [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] is enriched by the complexity of the pronounced mouldings and vitality of the carved [[Capital (architecture)|capitals]] in a foliate style known as "stiff leaf".{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=77}} The exterior has an Early English fa<U+00E7>ade displaying more than three hundred sculpted figures,{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=274}} and described by Harvey as "the supreme triumph of the combined [[plastic arts]] in England".{{sfn|Harvey|1961|p=63}} The eastern end retains much ancient [[stained glass]], which is rare in England.{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=274}}

Unlike the many English [[Cathedral#Late Middle Ages: monastic and secular cathedrals|cathedrals of monastic foundation]], Wells has an exceptional number of surviving secular buildings associated with its chapter of [[Canon (priest)|secular canons]], such as the [[Bishop's Palace, Wells|Bishop's Palace]] and the [[Vicars' Close, Wells|Vicars' Close]], a residential street which has remained intact from the 15th century.{{sfn|Swaan|1984|pp=188<U+2013>196}} The cathedral is a [[scheduled monument]] and is designated by [[English Heritage]] as a Grade I [[Listed building (United Kingdom)|listed building]].<ref name="ehlisting">{{NHLE |num=1382901 |desc=Cathedral Church of St Andrew, Chapter House and Cloisters |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=pastscape/>
{{TOC limit}}

==History==

===Early years===
The earliest remains of a building on the site are of a late [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[mausoleum]], identified during excavations in 1980.<ref name=pastscape>{{cite web |title=Wells Cathedral |url=http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=196971 |work=Pastscape&nbsp;<U+2013> National Monument Record |publisher=[[English Heritage]] |accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref>{{sfn|Adkins|1992|pp=118<U+2013>119}} An abbey church was built in [[Wells, Somerset|Wells]] in 705 by [[Aldhelm]], first bishop of the newly established [[Bishop of Sherborne|Diocese of Sherborne]] during the reign of King [[Ine of Wessex]].<ref name=britania>{{cite web|title=The History and Architecture of Wells Cathedral in Somerset, Part 1|url=http://www.britannia.com/history/somerset/churches/wellscath.html|publisher=Britannia|accessdate=11 July 2013}}</ref>{{sfn|Malden|1947|p=27}} It was dedicated to [[Andrew the Apostle|Saint Andrew]] and stood at the present site of the cathedral's [[cloister]]s, where some excavated remains can be seen. The [[baptismal font]] in the cathedral's south [[transept]] is from this church and is the oldest part of the present building.{{sfn|Pepin|2004|p=141}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Chronological History|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/history/timeline/|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref> In 766 [[Cynewulf of Wessex|Cynewulf]], [[List of monarchs of Wessex|King of Wessex]], signed a charter endowing the church with eleven [[Hide (unit)|hides]] of land.{{efn|name= Hides|A [[Hide (unit)|hide of land]] was a unit of land sufficient to support a family. Considered as a fiscal unit, the use of the hide in the [[Domesday Book]] shows that it was variable from county to county, but generally about 120 "acres" (not 120 acres of 4840 sq. yds. each, but 120 times the amount of land which a ploughteam of eight oxen could plough in a single day).<ref name=Hide>{{cite web|title=Glossary|url=http://www.domesdaybook.co.uk/glossary.html|publisher=Domesday Book Online|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref> }}<ref name="LapidgeBlair2013">{{cite book|last1=Lapidge|first1=Michael |last2=Blair|first2=John |last3=Keynes|first3=Simon |first4=Donald |last4=Scragg|title=The Wiley Blackwell Encyclopedia of Anglo-Saxon England|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=WaAzAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA243|date=2 October 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-31609-2|pages=243<U+2013>44|chapter=Hide}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wells Cathedral |url=http://webapp1.somerset.gov.uk/her/details.asp?prn=15381 |work=Somerset Historic Environment Record |publisher=[[Somerset County Council]] |accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> In 909 the seat of the diocese was moved from Sherborne to Wells.<ref name=pastscape/>

The first Bishop of Wells was [[Athelm]] (909), who crowned [[<U+00C6>thelstan|King <U+00C6>thelstan]]. Athelm and his nephew [[Dunstan]] both became [[Archbishop of Canterbury|Archbishops of Canterbury]].<ref name=britania/> During this period a choir of boys was established to sing the [[liturgy]]. <!---NOTE: The following sentence says EXACTLY what it means. The date of the school's foundation is controversial. --->[[Wells Cathedral School]] dates its foundation to this point.<ref>{{cite web |title=History |url=http://www.wellscathedralschool.org/wells/index.php/history |publisher=Wells Cathedral School |accessdate=2 February 2013}}</ref> Following the [[Norman conquest of England|Norman Conquest]], Bishop [[John of Tours|John de Villula]] moved the seat of the bishop from Wells to Bath in 1090.{{sfn|Tatton-Brown|Crook|2002|pp=74<U+2013>76}} The church at Wells, no longer a cathedral, had a college of [[secular clergy]].{{sfn|Tatton-Brown|Crook|2002|pp=74<U+2013>76}}

===Seat of the bishop===
The cathedral is thought to have been conceived and commenced in about 1175 by Bishop [[Reginald Fitz Jocelin]], who died in 1191.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=57}}{{sfn|Powicke|1961|p=251}}{{sfn|Matthews|2005|p=13}} Although it is clear from its size that, from the outset, the church was planned to be the cathedral of the diocese,{{sfn|Tatton-Brown|Crook|2002|pp=74<U+2013>76}} the seat of the bishop moved between Wells and the abbeys of [[Glastonbury Abbey|Glastonbury]] and [[Bath Abbey|Bath]], before settling at Wells. In 1197 Bishop Reginald's successor, Bishop [[Savaric FitzGeldewin]], with the approval of [[Pope Celestine III]], officially moved his seat to Glastonbury Abbey. The title of Bishop of Bath and Glastonbury was used until the Glastonbury claim was abandoned in 1219.{{sfn|Brooke|1976|pp=184<U+2013>185}}

Bishop Savaric's successor, [[Jocelin of Wells]], again moved the bishop's seat to Bath Abbey, with the title Bishop of Bath. Jocelin was a brother of [[Hugh of Wells|Bishop Hugh II of Lincoln]]<ref name=BHOBath>{{cite web |url=http://british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=34341 |title=Bishops |first=Diana E. |last=Greenway |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |year=2001 |work=Fasti Ecclesiae Anglicanae 1066<U+2013>1300: volume 7: Bath and Wells |accessdate=10 July 2013 }}</ref> and was present at the signing of the [[Magna Carta]]. Bishop Jocelin continued the building campaign begun by Bishop Reginald and was responsible for the [[Bishop's Palace, Wells|Bishop's Palace]], the [[choir|chorister]]s' school, a [[grammar school]], a hospital for travellers and a chapel. He also had a manor house built at [[Wookey]], near Wells.<ref name=DNB/> Jocelin saw the church dedicated in 1239 but, despite much lobbying of the pope by Jocelin's representatives in Rome, did not live to see cathedral status granted. The delay may have been a result of inaction by [[Pandulf Masca]], a Roman ecclesiastical politician, papal legate to England and [[Bishop of Norwich]], who was asked by the pope to investigate the situation but did not respond.{{sfn|Colchester|1987|p=15}} Jocelin died at Wells on 19 November 1242 and was buried in the choir of the cathedral;<ref name="BHOBath" /><ref name=DNB>{{cite web |last=Dunning |first=Robert |title=Wells, Jocelin of (d. 1242) |publisher=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography | url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/14831 |accessdate=15 November 2007}} {{ODNBsub}}</ref>{{sfn|Fryde|1986|p=228}} the [[Monumental brass|memorial brass]] on his tomb is one of the earliest brasses in England.<ref name=DNB/> Following his death the monks of Bath unsuccessfully attempted to regain authority over Wells.{{sfn|Robinson|1916|p=161}}

In 1245 the ongoing dispute over the title of the bishop was resolved by a ruling of [[Pope Innocent IV]] who established the title as the "Bishop of Bath and Wells", as it has remained until this day, with Wells as the principal seat of the bishop.{{sfn|Dunning|2001|p=41}} Since the 11th century the church has had a [[Cathedral chapter|chapter]] of secular clergy, like the cathedrals of [[Chichester Cathedral|Chichester]], [[Hereford Cathedral|Hereford]], [[Lincoln Cathedral|Lincoln]] and [[York Minster|York]]. The chapter was endowed with twenty-two [[prebendary|prebends]] (lands from which finance was drawn) and a provost to manage them. On acquiring cathedral status, in common with other such cathedrals, it had four chief clergy, the [[Dean (Christianity)|dean]], [[precentor]], [[Chancellor (ecclesiastical)|chancellor]] and [[sacristan]], who were responsible for the spiritual and material care of the cathedral.<ref name=CofEmedia>{{cite book |publisher=Church of England|last=Podmore|first=Colin|date=July 2008|chapterurl=http://www.churchofengland.org/media/40671/chapter5.pdf |format=PDF |title=Dioceses and Episcopal Sees in England|chapter=Chapter 5: Old Foundation cathedrals }}</ref>

