===Building the cathedral===
The building program which was begun by Bishop Reginald Fitz Jocelin in the 12th century continued under Jocelin of Wells, who was a canon from 1200, then bishop from 1206. Adam Locke was master mason from about 1192 until 1230.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}}  It was designed in the new style with pointed arches, later known as [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]], and which was introduced at about the same time at [[Canterbury Cathedral]].{{sfn|Harvey|1987|pp=57<U+2013>58}}  Work was halted between 1209 and 1213 when [[John, King of England|King John]] was [[Excommunication|excommunicated]] and Bishop Jocelin was in exile,{{sfn|Reid|1963|pp=40<U+2013>41}} but the main parts of the church were complete by the time of the dedication by Bishop Jocelin in 1239.{{sfn|Tatton-Brown|Crook|2002|pp=74<U+2013>76}}

By the time the cathedral, including the [[chapter house]], was finished in 1306,<ref name=sacred>{{cite web |url=http://www.sacred-destinations.com/england/wells-cathedral |title=Wells Cathedral |accessdate=3 February 2013 |publisher=Sacred destinations }}</ref> it was already too small for the developing liturgy, and unable to accommodate increasingly grand processions of clergy. Bishop [[John Droxford]] initiated another phase of building under master mason Thomas of Whitney,<ref name=sacred/> during which the central tower was heightened and an eight-sided [[Lady chapel]], completed by 1326, was added at the east end.<ref name=isleofavalon>{{cite web |url=http://www.isleofalbion.co.uk/sites/102/wells_cathedral.php |title=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=3 February 2013 |publisher=Isle of Albion }}</ref> Bishop [[Ralph of Shrewsbury]] followed, continuing the eastward extension of the choir and [[retrochoir]] beyond. He oversaw the building of [[Vicars' Close, Wells|Vicars' Close]] and the Vicars' Hall, to give the men who were employed to sing in the choir a secure place to live and dine, away from the town and its temptations.<ref name="localhist">{{cite web |url=http://www.wells-uk.com/local_history.php |title=Local history |accessdate=10 February 2008 |publisher=Wells UK |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071224145315/http://www.wells-uk.com/local_history.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=24 December 2007}}</ref> He had an uneasy relationship with the citizens of Wells, partly because of his imposition of taxes,<ref name="localhist" /> and he surrounded his palace with [[Battlement|crenellated]] walls, a moat and a drawbridge.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/catalogue/adsdata/arch-769-1/dissemination/pdf/vol26/26_069_100.pdf |title=Hierarchism in Conventual Crenellation |last=Coulson |first=Charles |publisher=Society for Medieval Archaeology|format=PDF |accessdate=24 February 2013|journal=Medieval Archaeology|volume= 26 |pages=pp. 69<U+2013>100|ref=harv}}{{registration required}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bishopspalace.org.uk/attachments/The%20Palace%20Rooms.pdf |title=Bishop's Palace Timeline |publisher=Bishops Palace |format=PDF |accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref>

Bishop [[John Harewell]] raised money for the completion of the west front by [[William Wynford]], who was appointed as master mason in 1365. One of the foremost architects of his time, Wynford worked for the king at [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]], [[Winchester Cathedral]] and [[New College, Oxford]].{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=352}} At Wells, he designed the western towers of which north-west was not built until the following century.{{sfn|Wade|1926|p=257}} In the 14th century, the central [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] of the [[crossing (architecture)|crossing]] were found to be sinking under the weight of the crossing tower which had been damaged by an earthquake the previous century.<ref name=cathbrit>{{cite web |title=The cathedrals of Britain |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/architecture_cathedral_01.shtml |publisher=BBC |accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> Strainer arches, sometimes described as scissor arches, were inserted by master mason [[William Joy (master mason)|William Joy]] to brace and stabilise the piers as a unit.<ref name=cathbrit/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://timeref.com/hpl285.htm |title=Wells Cathedral |accessdate=10 February 2008 |publisher=Timeref }}</ref>

===Tudors and Civil War===
By the reign of [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] the cathedral building was complete, appearing much as it does today (though the fittings have changed considerably). From 1508 to 1546, the eminent Italian [[Renaissance humanism|humanist]] scholar [[Polydore Vergil]] was active as the chapter's representative in London. He donated a set of hangings for the [[Choir (architecture)|choir]] of the cathedral.{{sfn|Hay|1952|pp=8<U+2013>20}}<ref>{{cite journal |first=Oliver |last=Harris |title=Polydore Vergil's hangings in the quire of Wells Cathedral |journal=Somerset Archaeology and Local History |volume=149 |year=2006 |pages=71<U+2013>77 |ref=harv }}</ref> While Wells survived the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]] better than those cathedrals of monastic foundation, the abolition of chantries in 1547 resulted in a reduction in the cathedral's income. [[Middle Ages|Medieval]] brasses were sold, and a [[pulpit]] was placed in the [[nave]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/history/timeline/the-reformation/ |title=The Reformation |accessdate=2 September 2011 |publisher=Wells Cathedral }}</ref> Between 1551 and 1568, in two periods as dean, [[William Turner (naturalist)|William Turner]] established a [[Herb garden|herbal garden]], which was recreated between 2003 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.olddeanerygarden.org.uk/index.php |title=The Old Deanery Garden, Wells |author=The Diocese of Bath and Wells |work=olddeanerygarden.org.uk |year=2013 |accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Adler |first=Mark |date=May 2010|title=Haunt of ancient peace |publisher=''Mendip Times'' |pages=36<U+2013>37}}</ref>

[[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] gave the chapter and the Vicars Choral a new charter in 1591, creating a new governing body, consisting of the dean and eight residentiary canons with control over the church estates and authority over its affairs, but no longer entitled to elect the dean (that entitlement thenceforward belonged ultimately to [[the Crown]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=40953 |title=Colleges: The cathedral of Wells |editor-first=William|editor-last= Page |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |year=1911 |work=A History of the County of Somerset: Volume 2 |accessdate=3 January 2013 }}</ref> The stability brought by the new charter ended with the onset of the [[English Civil War|Civil War]] and the execution of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]. Local fighting damaged the cathedral's stonework, furniture and windows. The dean, [[Walter Raleigh (priest)|Walter Raleigh]], a nephew of the explorer [[Walter Raleigh|Sir Walter Raleigh]], was placed under house arrest after the fall of [[Bridgwater]] to the [[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]] in 1645, first  in the rectory at [[Chedzoy]] and then in the deanery at Wells.<ref>{{cite web |last=Marchant |first=E.C. |title=Ralegh, Walter (1586<U+2013>1646) Dean of Wells |publisher=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography | url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/23040 |accessdate=15 November 2007}} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> His jailer, the shoe maker and city constable, David Barrett, caught him writing a letter to his wife. When he refused to surrender it, Barrett ran him through with a sword and he died six weeks later, on 10 October 1646.<ref name="bbc-parod">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/somerset/content/articles/2007/10/24/elizabeth_feature.shtml |title=Hollywood parodies real life drama in Wells |accessdate=10 February 2008 |publisher=BBC|date=24 October 2010}}</ref> He was buried in an unmarked grave in the choir before the dean's stall.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Ralegh, Walter (1586<U+2013>1646)|volume=47}}</ref> During the [[Commonwealth of England]] under [[Oliver Cromwell]] no dean was appointed and the cathedral fell into disrepair. The then bishop went into retirement and some of the clerics were reduced to performing menial tasks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Destruction and Disaster |url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/history/timeline/destruction-and-disaster/ |publisher=Wells Cathedral |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref>

===1660<U+2013>1800===
In 1661, after [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] was restored to the throne, [[Robert Creighton]], who had served as the king's chaplain in exile, was appointed dean and then served as the bishop for two years before his death in 1672.{{sfn|Lehmberg|1996|p=55}} His brass [[lectern]], given in thanksgiving, can be seen in the cathedral. He also donated the great west window of the nave at a cost of <U+00A3>140. Following Creighton's appointment as bishop, [[Ralph Bathurst]], who had been chaplain to the king, president of [[Trinity College, Oxford]] and fellow of the [[Royal Society]],{{sfn|Hopkins|2005|p=161}} became dean. During Bathurst's long tenure the cathedral was restored, however in the [[Monmouth Rebellion]] of 1685, Puritan soldiers damaged the west front, tore lead from the roof to make bullets, broke the windows, smashed the organ and furnishings, and for a time stabled their horses in the nave.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.somerset.gov.uk/archives/ASH/Monmouthreb.htm |title=The Monmouth rebellion and the bloody assize |accessdate=11 February 2008 |publisher=[[Somerset County Council]] }}</ref>

Restoration began again under Bishop [[Thomas Ken]] who was appointed by the Crown in 1685 and served until 1691. He was one of seven bishops imprisoned for refusing to sign [[James II of England|King James II's]] "[[Declaration of Indulgence]]", which would have enabled Catholics to resume positions of political power, but popular support led to their acquittal. Ken refused to take the oath of allegiance to [[William and Mary]] because James II had not abdicated and with others, known as the [[Nonjuring schism|Nonjurors]], was put out of office.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ollard|first=S.L.|editor-first1=S.L.|editor-last1=Ollard|editor-first2=Gordon|editor-last2=Crosse|title=A Dictionary of English Church History|chapter=The Nonjurors|chapterurl=http://anglicanhistory.org/nonjurors/ollard_crosse1912.html|publisher=Mowbray and Co.|date=1912}}</ref> His successor, [[Richard Kidder|Bishop Kidder]], was killed in the [[Great Storm of 1703]] when two chimney stacks on the palace fell on him and his wife, while they were asleep in bed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Kidder (1633<U+2013>1703), Bishop of Bath and Wells (1691<U+2013>1703) |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/richard-kidder-16331703-bishop-of-bath-and-wells-16911703-39388 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Cassan|first=Stephen Hyde|title=Lives of the Bishops of Bath|year=1829|publisher=C and J Rivington|page=163|url=http://books.google.com/?id=OJgAAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA1-PA163&lpg=RA1-PA163&dq=Bishop+Kidder+1703+death#v=onepage&q=Bishop%20Kidder%201703%20death&f=false}}</ref>

