===Victorian era to present===
By the middle of the 19th century, a major [[Victorian restoration|restoration programme]] was needed. Under [[Edmund Goodenough|Dean Goodenough]], the monuments were moved to the cloisters and the remaining medieval paint and [[whitewash]] was removed in an operation known as "the great scrape".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/history/timeline/249-2/ |title=Victorian Restorations |accessdate=2 September 2011 |publisher=Wells Cathedral }}</ref> [[Anthony Salvin]] took charge of the extensive restoration of the choir. Wooden galleries that had been installed in the 16th century were removed and the stalls were given stone canopies and placed further back within the line of the arcade. The medieval stone [[pulpitum]] screen was extended in the centre to support a new [[organ (music)|organ]].{{sfn|Colchester|1987|pp=126<U+2013>7}}

The late 20th century saw an extensive restoration programme, particularly of the west front.{{sfn|Hatton|1999|pp=218<U+2013>230}}<ref name=westfrontrestore>{{cite web |title=The West Front Restoration |url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/history/heritage-conservation/the-west-front-restoration/ |publisher=Wells Cathedral |accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref> The stained glass is currently under restoration, with a programme underway to conserve the large 14th-century [[Tree of Jesse|Jesse Tree]] window at the eastern terminal of the choir.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Jesse Window Project&nbsp;<U+2013> An Update (November 2012) |url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/history/heritage-conservation/the-jesse-window-project/|publisher=Wells Cathedral |accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=vidimus>{{cite journal |title=Conservation of 'Tree of Jesse' Window at Wells Cathedral |journal=Vidimus |date=September 2010|issue=43 |url=http://vidimus.org/issues/issue-43/news/ |accessdate=24 February 2013 |ref=harv}}</ref>

==Ministry==
Since the 13th century Wells Cathedral has been the seat of the [[Bishop of Bath and Wells]]. Its governing body, the [[Chapter (religion)|chapter]], is made up of five clerical canons (the dean, the precentor, the canon chancellor, the canon treasurer, and the archdeacon of Wells) and four lay members: the administrator (chief executive), Keeper of the Fabric, Overseer of the Estate and the chairman of the cathedral shop and catering boards.<ref name="Chapter">{{cite web|title=The Cathedral Chapter|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/whos-who-contact/the-cathedral-chapter/|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> The most recent Bishop of Bath and Wells was [[Peter Price (bishop)|Peter Price]], who was appointed in 2001 and retired on 30 June 2013.{{efn|name=Bishop}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Bishop Peter Price&nbsp;<U+2013> biography and publications |url=http://www.bathandwells.org.uk/diocese/bishop-peter-price-biography/ |publisher=Diocese of Bath and Wells |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> The present dean is [[John Clarke (dean of Wells)|John Clarke]].<ref name=dean/>

Employed staff include the organist and master of choristers, head [[Verger|virger]], archivist, librarian and the staff of the shop, caf<U+00E9> and restaurant.<ref>{{cite web|title=Heads of Departments|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/whos-who-contact/heads-of-departments/|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> The chapter is advised by specialists such as architects, archaeologists and financial experts.<ref name="Chapter"/>

More than a thousand services are held each year. There are daily services of [[Matins]], Holy Communion and Choral Evensong,<ref>{{cite web|title=General Services & Calendar|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/worship/general-services-calendar/|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> as well as major celebrations of Christian festivals such as [[Christmas]], [[Easter]], [[Pentecost]] and [[Saint's Day|saints' days]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Worship|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/worship/|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> The cathedral is also used for the baptisms, weddings and funerals of those with close connections to it.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baptisms, Weddings and Funerals|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/worship/baptisms-weddings-and-funerals/|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> In July 2009 the cathedral hosted the funeral of [[Harry Patch]], the last [[British Army]] veteran of [[World War I]], who died at the age of 111.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8186578.stm | publisher=BBC | title=Last Post salute for WWI veteran | date= 6 August 2009 |accessdate=3 February 2013}}</ref>

Three Sunday services are led by the resident choir (during the school terms) and choral services are sung on weekdays. The cathedral hosts visiting choirs and is involved in outreach work with local schools as part of its Chorister Outreach Project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Outreach|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/music-the-choir/music-outreach/|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> The cathedral is also the venue for musical events such as an annual concert by the [[Somerset Chamber Choir]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Somerset Chamber Choir past concerts |url=http://www.somersetchamberchoir.performers.co.uk/past_concerts.html |publisher=Somerset Chamber Choir |accessdate=22 December 2011}}</ref>

Each year approximately 150,000 people attend services and another 300,000 visit as tourists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Background Information to the Post of Archivist|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Archivist-Application-Pack-v2.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> Entry is free, but visitors are encouraged to make a donation towards the annual running costs which were around <U+00A3>2 million (approx. US$3.3 million) in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cathedral will remain free to visitors as matter of principle |url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/Cathedral-remain-free-visitors-matter-principle/story-12316135-detail/story.html#axzz2kYRRp4WP |publisher=Western Daily Press|date=19 August 2010|accessdate=13 November 2013|first1=Will|last1= Chivers |first2=Jo |last2=Jefferis}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==Architecture==

===Dates, styles and architects ===
[[File:WellsCathPlan numbered.JPG|thumb|upright=2.15|1. West front 2. Nave 3. Central tower 4. Choir 5. Retrochoir 6. Lady Chapel 7. Aisle 8. Transept 9. East transept 10. North porch 11. Chapter house 12. Cloister <br /><center>(adapted from a plan by [[Georg Dehio]])</center>]]

Construction of the cathedral began in about 1175, to the design of an unknown architect. Wells is the first cathedral in England to be, from its foundation, built in the Gothic style. According to art historian [[John Harvey (historian)|John Harvey]], it is the first truly Gothic cathedral in the world, its architects having entirely dispensed with all the features that bound the contemporary east end of Canterbury Cathedral and the earlier buildings of France, such as the east end of the [[Basilica of Saint Denis|Abbey of Saint Denis]], to the Romanesque.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=19}} Unlike these churches, Wells has clustered piers rather than columns and has a gallery of identical pointed arches rather than the typically Romanesque form of paired openings. The style, with its simple untraceried [[lancet arch]]es and convoluted mouldings, is known as [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English Gothic]].{{sfn|Fletcher|1961|pp=189<U+2013>90}}

From about 1192 to 1230, Adam Lock, the earliest architect at Wells for whom a name is known, continued the transept and nave in the same manner as his predecessor.  Lock was also builder of the north porch, to his own design.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}}

The Early English west front was commenced around 1230 by Thomas Norreys, with building and sculpture continuing for thirty years.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}} Its south-west tower was begun 100 years later and constructed between 1365 and 1395, and the north-west tower between 1425 and 1435, both in the [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular Gothic]] style to the design of William Wynford, {{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}} who also filled many of the cathedral's early English [[lancet window]]s with delicate [[tracery]].{{sfn|Wade|1926|p=257}}
Between 1275 and 1310 the [[undercroft]] and chapterhouse were built by unknown architects, the undercroft in the Early English and the chapter house in the Geometric style of [[English Gothic architecture#Decorated Gothic|Decorated Gothic]] architecture. In about 1310 work commenced on the Lady Chapel, to the design of Thomas Witney, who also built the central tower from 1315 to 1322 in the Decorated Gothic style.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}} The tower was later braced internally with arches by William Joy.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}} Concurrent with this work, in 1329<U+2013>45 Joy made alterations and extensions to the choir, joining it to the Lady Chapel with the retrochoir, the latter in the [[English Gothic#Decorated Gothic|Flowing Decorated]] style.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}}

Later changes include the Perpendicular vault of the tower and construction of Sugar's Chapel, 1475<U+2013>90 by [[William Smyth (architect)|William Smyth]].  Also, Gothic Revival renovations were made to the choir and pulpitum by [[Benjamin Ferrey]] and Anthony Salvin, 1842<U+2013>57.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}}

===Plan===
Wells has a total length of {{convert|415|ft|m}}. In common with Canterbury, Lincoln and [[Salisbury Cathedral|Salisbury]] cathedrals, it has the distinctly English arrangement of two transepts, with the body of the church divided into distinct parts: nave, choir, and retrochoir, beyond which extends the Lady Chapel.{{sfn|Swaan|1984|pp=173<U+2013>174}} The fa<U+00E7>ade is wide, with its towers extending beyond the transepts on either side.{{sfn|Swaan|1984|pp=188<U+2013>196}} There is a large projecting porch on the north side of the nave forming an entry into the cathedral.{{sfn|Pevsner|1958|pp=278<U+2013>310}} To the north-east is the large octagonal chapter house, entered from the north choir aisle by a passage and staircase. To the south of the nave is a large cloister, unusual in that the northern range, that adjacent the cathedral, was never built.{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=136}}

===Elevation===
In section, the cathedral has the usual arrangement of a large church: a central nave with an aisle on each side, separated by two arcades. The elevation is in three stages, [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]], [[Triforium|triforium gallery]] and [[clerestory]].{{sfn|Pevsner|1958|pp=278<U+2013>310}} The nave is {{convert|67|ft|m}} in height, very low compared to the Gothic cathedrals of France.{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|pp=74<U+2013>79}} It has a markedly horizontal emphasis, caused by the triforium having a unique form, a series of identical narrow openings, lacking the usual definition of the bays. The triforium is separated from the arcade by a single horizontal [[string course]] that runs unbroken the length of the nave. There are no vertical lines linking the three stages, as the shafts supporting the vault rise above the triforium.{{sfn|Pevsner|1958|pp=278<U+2013>310}}

