===Exterior===
The exterior of Wells Cathedral presents a relatively tidy and harmonious appearance since the greater part of the building was executed in a single style, [[Early English Gothic]]. This is uncommon among English cathedrals where the exterior usually exhibits a plethora of styles.<ref name=reeve/> At Wells, later changes in the Perpendicular style were universally applied, such as filling the Early English lancet windows with simple tracery, the construction of a [[parapet]] that encircles the roof, and the addition of [[pinnacle]]s framing each [[gable]], similar to those around the chapter house and on the west front.{{sfn|Pevsner|1958|pp=278<U+2013>310}} At the eastern end there is a proliferation of tracery with repeated motifs in the Reticulated style, a stage between Geometric and Flowing Decorated tracery.{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|pp=156<U+2013>158}}

====West front====
The west front is {{convert|100|ft|m|0}} high and {{convert|147|ft|m|0}} wide,{{sfn|Colchester|1987|p=183}} and built of [[Inferior Oolite]] of the [[Middle Jurassic]] period, which came from the [[Doulting Stone Quarry]], about {{convert|8|mi|km|0}} to the east.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://doultingstonequarry.co.uk/?Quarry_History |archiveurl=http://wayback.archive.org/web/20130814102745/http://doultingstonequarry.co.uk/?Quarry_History |archivedate=2013-08-14 |publisher=Doulting Stone |title=Quarry History |accessdate=12 November 2010}}</ref> According to the [[architectural historian]] [[Alec Clifton-Taylor]], it is "one of the great sights of England".{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=78}}

West fronts in general take three distinct forms: those that follow the elevation of the nave and aisles, those that have paired towers at the end of each aisle, framing the nave, and those that screen the form of the building. The west front at Wells has the paired-tower form, unusual in that the towers do not indicate the location of the aisles, but extend well beyond them, screening the dimensions and profile of the building.{{sfn|Swaan|1984|pp=188<U+2013>196}}

The west front rises in three distinct stages, each clearly defined by a horizontal course. This horizontal emphasis is counteracted by six strongly projecting buttresses defining the cross-sectional divisions of nave, aisles and towers, and are highly decorated, each having canopied niches containing the largest statues on the fa<U+00E7>ade.{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=78}}

At the lowest level of the fa<U+00E7>ade is a plain base, contrasting with and stabilising the ornate arcades that rise above it.{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=78}} The base is penetrated by three doors, which are in stark contrast to the often imposing portals of French Gothic cathedrals. The outer two are of domestic proportion and the central door is ornamented only by a central post, [[quatrefoil]] and the fine mouldings of the arch.{{sfn|Swaan|1984|pp=188<U+2013>196}}

Above the basement rise two storeys, ornamented with quatrefoils and niches originally holding about four hundred statues, with three hundred surviving until the mid-20th century.{{sfn|Swaan|1984|pp=188<U+2013>196}} Since then, some have been restored or replaced, including the ruined figure of Christ in the gable.<ref name=Caroe/>

The third stages of the flanking towers were both built in the Perpendicular style of the late 14th century, to the design of William Wynford; that on the north-west was not begun until about 1425.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}} The design maintains the general proportions, and continues the strong projection of the buttresses.

The finished product has been criticised for its lack of pinnacles, and it is probable that the towers were intended to carry spires which were never built.{{sfn|Pevsner|1958|pp=278<U+2013>310}} Despite its lack of spires or pinnacles, the architectural historian [[Sir Banister Fletcher|Banister Fletcher]] describes it as "the highest development in English Gothic of this type of facade." {{sfn|Fletcher|1961|p=421}}

