====Crossing tower====
The central tower appears to date from the early 13th century. It was substantially reconstructed in the early 14th century during the remodelling of the east end, necessitating the internal bracing of the piers a decade or so later. In the 14th century the tower was given a timber and lead spire which burnt down in 1439. The exterior was then reworked in the Perpendicular style and given the present parapet and pinnacles.{{sfn|Tatton-Brown|Crook|2002|pp=74<U+2013>76}} Alec Clifton-Taylor describes it as "outstanding even in Somerset, a county famed for the splendour of its church towers".{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=274}}

====North porch====
The north porch is described by art historian [[Nikolaus Pevsner]] as "sumptuously decorated", and intended to be the main entrance.{{sfn|Pevsner|1958|pp=278<U+2013>310}} Externally it is simple and rectangular with plain side walls. The entrance is a steeply arched portal framed by rich mouldings of eight shafts with stiff-leaf capitals each encircled by an [[Annulet (architecture)|annular]] moulding at middle height. Those on the left are figurative, containing images representing the martyrdom of St [[Edmund the Martyr]].{{sfn|Pevsner|1958|pp=278<U+2013>310}} The walls are lined with deep niches framed by narrow shafts with capitals and annulets like those of the portal.

====Cloisters====
The cloisters were built in the late 13th century and largely rebuilt from 1430 to 1508{{sfn|Tatton-Brown|Crook|2002|pp=74<U+2013>76}}{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}} and have wide openings divided by [[mullion]]s and [[Transom (architectural)|transom]]s, and tracery in the  Perpendicular Gothic style. The vault has [[Lierne (vault)|lierne]] ribs that form octagons at the centre of each compartment, the joints of each rib having decorative [[Boss (architecture)|bosses]].{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=226}} The eastern range is of two storeys, of which the upper is the library built in the 15th century.{{sfn|Tatton-Brown|Crook|2002|pp=74<U+2013>76}}

Because Wells Cathedral was secular rather than monastic, cloisters were not a practical necessity. They were omitted from several other secular cathedrals but were built here and at Chichester. Explanations for their construction at these two secular cathedrals range from the processional to the aesthetic.{{sfn|Clifton-Taylor|1967|p=136}} As at Chichester, there is no northern range to the cloisters. In monastic cloisters it was the north range, benefiting most from winter sunlight, that was often used as a [[scriptorium]].{{sfn|Crossley|1962|pp=67<U+2013>68}}

