===Fittings and monuments===
Some of the cathedral's fittings and monuments are hundreds of years old. The [[brass]] lectern in the Lady Chapel dates from 1661, and has a moulded stand and foliate crest.<ref name=reeve>{{cite journal|last=Reeve|first=Matthew M.|title=The Capital Sculpture of Wells Cathedral : Masons, Patrons and the Margins of English Gothic Architecture|journal=Journal of the British Archaeological Association|year=2010|volume=163|pages=72<U+2013>109|doi=10.1179/174767010x12747977921047|url=http://www.academia.edu/1272708/The_Capital_Sculpture_of_Wells_Cathedral_Masons_Patrons_and_the_Margins_of_English_Gothic_Architecture|ref=harv}}</ref> In the north transept chapel is a 17th-century oak screen with columns, formerly part of cow stalls, with artisan [[Ionic order|Ionic]] capitals and cornice, which is set forward over the chest tomb of [[John Godelee]]. There is a bound oak chest from the 14th century which was used to store the chapter seal and key documents. The Bishop's Throne dates from 1340, and has a panelled, canted front and stone doorway, and a deep nodding cusped ogee canopy above it, with three-stepped [[Niche (architecture)|statue niches]] and pinnacles. The throne was restored by Anthony Salvin around 1850.<ref name=ehlisting /> Opposite the throne is a 19th-century octagonal pulpit on a coved base with panelled sides, and steps up from the north aisle. The round font in the south transept is from the former [[Anglo-Saxon England|Saxon]] cathedral and has an arcade of round-headed arches, on a round [[plinth]]. The font cover was made in 1635 and is decorated with the heads of [[Putto|putti]]. The Chapel of [[Martin of Tours|St Martin]] is a memorial to every Somerset man who fell in World War I.{{sfn|Leete-Hodge|1985|p=20}}

The monuments and tombs include: [[Gisa (bishop of Wells)|Bishop Gisa]], died 1088; [[William of Bitton II|Bishop Bytton]], died 1274; Bishop [[William of March]], died 1302; John Droxford, died 1329; John Godelee, died 1333; John Middleton, died c1350; Ralph of Shrewsbury, died 1363; Bishop Harewell, died 1386; William Bykonyll, died c1448; John Bernard, died 1459; [[Thomas Beckington|Bishop Bekynton]], died 1464; [[John Gunthorpe]], died 1498; [[John Still]], died 1607; [[Robert Creighton]], died 1672; Bishop Kidder, died 1703; [[George Hooper|Bishop Hooper]], died 1727 and [[Lord Arthur Hervey|Bishop Harvey]], died 1894.{{sfn|Malden|1947|pp=52<U+2013>54}}

===Clock===
In the north transept is [[Wells Cathedral clock]], an [[astronomical clock]] from about 1325, believed to be the work of Peter Lightfoot, a monk of Glastonbury.{{sfn|Cox|2008|p=183}} Its mechanism, dated to between 1386 and 1392, was replaced in the 19th century, and the original mechanism moved to the [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]] in London, where it continues to operate. It is the second-oldest surviving clock in England, after the [[Salisbury cathedral clock]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/objects/time_measurement/1884-77.aspx |title=Wells Cathedral clock, c.1392 |accessdate=11 February 2008 |publisher=Science Museum }}</ref>

The clock has its original medieval face. As well as showing the time on a 24-hour dial, it reflects the motion of the Sun and Moon, the [[Lunar phase|phases of the Moon]], and the time since the last new Moon. The astronomical dial represents a [[Geocentric model|geocentric]] or pre-[[Copernican Revolution|Copernican]] view of the universe, with the Sun and Moon revolving round a central fixed Earth, like that of the clock at [[Ottery St Mary]].<ref name=isleofavalon/> Every quarter hour the clock is chimed by a quarter jack in the form of a small [[automaton]] known as Jack Blandifers, who hits two bells with hammers and two with his heels.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.horologica.co.uk/horology/Wells.html |publisher=Horologica|title=World's oldest clock? Doubtful|accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> At the striking of the clock [[jousting]] knights appear above the clock face.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Clock|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/history/historical-highlights/the-clock/|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref> 

On the outer wall of the transept, opposite Vicars' Hall, is a second clock face of the same clock, placed there just over seventy years after the interior clock and driven by the same mechanism. The second clock face has two quarter jacks (which strike on the quarter hour) in the form of knights in armour.{{sfn|Bedford|2007|p=23}}

In 2010 the official clock-winder retired and was replaced by an electric mechanism.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/7953673/Worlds-oldest-mechanical-clock-to-be-wound-by-hand-for-last-time.html |title=World's oldest mechanical clock 'to be wound by hand for last time' |accessdate=21 August 2010 |publisher=''Daily Telegraph'' | location=London | first=Andrew | last=Hough | date=20 August 2010}}</ref>

