==Music==
{{See also|List of musicians at English cathedrals}}

===Organ and organists===
The first record of an organ at this church dates from 1310, and a smaller organ, probably for the Lady Chapel, was installed in 1415. In 1620 an organ, built by [[Thomas Dallam]], was installed at a cost of <U+00A3>398 1s 5d.(equivalent to about <U+00A3>75,000  as of 2012{{efn|name=GDP|The method of calculation used is the historic opportunity cost of a project measured by comparing its relative cost using the cost index of all output in the economy. This measure uses the [[GDP deflator]].<ref name=MeasuringWorth1>{{cite web |last=Officer |first=Lawrence H. |contribution=Five Ways to Compute the Relative Value of a UK Pound Amount, 1830 to Present |url=http://www.measuringworth.com/ukcompare/ |publisher=measuringworth.com |accessdate=1 January 2014 |ref=harv |postscript=<!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to "." for the cite to end in a ".", as necessary. -->{{inconsistent citations}}}}</ref>}}).

The organ that was installed in 1620 was destroyed by parliamentary soldiers in 1643. An organ built in 1662 was enlarged in 1786 and again in 1855.<ref name=npor>{{cite web |url=http://www.npor.org.uk/cgi-bin/Rsearch.cgi?Fn=Rsearch&rec_index=N06889 |title=Somerset, Wells Cathedral of St. Andrew, Dean & Chapter of Wells N0 6890|accessdate=11 February 2008 |publisher=National Pipe Organ Register (NPOR) }}</ref> In 1909<U+2013>1910 an organ was built by [[Harrison & Harrison]] of Durham with the best parts of the old organ retained, and it has been maintained by the same company since.<ref name=npor/>

The first recorded [[List of organists and assistant organists of Wells Cathedral|organist of Wells Cathedral]] was Walter Bagele (or Vageler) in 1416,<ref>{{cite web|title=Walter Bagele|url=http://www.organ-biography.info/index.php?id=Bagele_Walter_15|publisher=Biographical Dictionary of the Organ|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> and the post of organist or assistant organist has been held by more than 60 individuals since then. Between 1996 and 2004 the appointed [[Organist and Master of the Choristers]] was [[Malcolm Archer]]. Since 2005 the organist has been Matthew Owens.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matthew Owens|url=http://wcos.org.uk/about-us/matthew-owens|publisher=Wells Cathedral Oratorio Society|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref> Jonathan Vaughn was appointed assistant organist in 2007, and the current organ scholars are Owain Park and William Fox.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/music-the-choir/ |title=Music |publisher=Wells Cathedral |date= |accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref>

===Cathedral Choir===
There has been a choir of boy choristers at Wells since 909. Currently there are eighteen boy choristers aged from eight to fourteen years.<ref name=choir/> The Vicars Choral was formed in the 12th century and the sung liturgy was provided by a traditional cathedral choir of men and boys, until the formation of an additional choir of girls in 1994. The boys and girls sing alternately with the Vicars Choral, and are educated at Wells Cathedral School.<ref>{{cite web |title=Choristers |url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/music-the-choir/choristers/ |publisher=Wells Cathedral |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>
The Vicars Choral currently number twelve men, of whom three are choral scholars. Since 1348 the College of Vicars has had its own accommodation. The Vicars Choral generally perform with the choristers, except on Wednesdays, when they sing alone, enabling them to present a different repertoire.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/music-the-choir/the-vicars-choral/ |title=The Vicars Choral |publisher=Wells Cathedral |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>

In December 2010 Wells Cathedral Choir was rated by ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]'' magazine as "the highest ranking choir with children in the world",<ref name=choir>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/music-the-choir/music-and-the-choir/ |title=Wells Cathedral Choir|publisher=Wells Cathedral | accessdate=30 December 2013}}</ref> and continues to provide music for the liturgy at Sunday and weekday services. The choir has made many recordings and toured frequently, including performances in Beijing and Hong Kong in 2012. Its repertoire ranges from the choral music of the [[Renaissance music|Renaissance]] to recently commissioned works.<ref name=choir/>

===Voluntary Choir===
The Wells Cathedral Voluntary Choir is a mixed adult choir of thirty members. It was formed in 1986 to sing at the midnight service on Christmas Eve, and was invited to sing at several other special services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wells Cathedral Voluntary Choir|url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/music-the-choir/wells-cathedral-voluntary-choir/|publisher=Wells Cathedral|accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> The choir now sings about fifty services a year when the Cathedral Choir is in recess or on tour, and spends one week a year singing as the "choir in residence" at another cathedral. Although primarily liturgical, the choir's repertoire also includes other forms of music as well as performances at engagements such as weddings and funerals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/music-the-choir/wells-cathedral-voluntary-choir/ |title=The Wells Cathedral Voluntary Choir |publisher=Wells Cathedral |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>

==Bells==
The bells at Wells Cathedral are the heaviest ring of ten bells in the world,<ref>{{cite web |title=Volunteer |url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/how-you-can-help/volunteering-at-wells/ |publisher=Wells Cathedral |accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref> the tenor bell (the 10th and largest), known as Harewell, weighing {{convert|56.25|long cwt|kg|lk=on}}.{{sfn|Colchester|1987|p=21}} They are hung for full circle ringing in the English style of [[change ringing]]. These bells are now hung in the south west tower, although some were originally hung in the central tower.{{sfn|Colchester|1987|p=52}}

