==Library==

The library is above the eastern cloister, and was built between 1430 and 1508.{{sfn|Harvey|1987|p=163}} The library's collection is in three parts: early documents, housed in the [[Muniment]] Room; the collection predating 1800, housed in the Chained Library; and the post-1800 collection, housed in the Reading Room.<ref name="library"/> The chapter's earlier collection was destroyed during the Reformation, so the present library consists chiefly of early printed books, rather than medieval manuscripts.<ref name="library"/> The earlier books, in the Chained Library, number 2,800 volumes and give an indication of the variety of interests of the members of the cathedral chapter from the Reformation until 1800. The focus of the collection is predominantly theology but there are volumes on science, medicine, exploration, and languages. Books of particular interest include [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny's]] ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Natural History]]'' printed in 1472, an ''[[Theatrum Orbis Terrarum|Atlas of the World]]'' by [[Abraham Ortelius]], printed in 1606 and a set of the works of [[Aristotle]] that once belonged to [[Erasmus]].<ref name="library">{{cite web | url=http://www.wellscathedral.org.uk/history/library-archives/ | publisher=Wells Cathedral | title=Library & Archives | accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> The library is open to the public at appointed times during summer and has a small exhibition of documents and books.<ref name="library"/>

===Original records===
Three early registers of the dean and chapter of Wells&nbsp;<U+2013> the ''Liber Albus I'' (White Book; R I), ''Liber Albus II'' (R III) and ''Liber Ruber'' (Red Book; R II, section i)&nbsp;<U+2013> were edited by W. H. B. Bird for the [[Royal Commission on Historical Manuscripts|Historical Manuscripts Commissioners]] and published in 1907.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Black Book of Winchester|last1=Bird|first1=W.H.B.|last2=Baigent|first2=F.J.|year=1925|publisher=Winchester: Warren & Son Limited|page=241}}</ref>  The books comprise, with some repetition, a [[cartulary]] of possessions of the cathedral, with grants of land dating back as early as the 8th century, well before the development of hereditary surnames in England; they also comprise acts of the dean and chapter, and surveys of their estates, mostly in Somerset.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theoriginalrecord.com/database/search/decade/100 | publisher=Theoriginalrecord.com | title=Liber Albus I (White Book; R I), Liber Albus II (R III), and Liber Ruber (Red Book; R II, section i) indexed by surname | accessdate=11 July 2013}}</ref>

==Environs and associated buildings==
{{multiple image
 | align = centre
 | direction = horizontal
 | header_align = center
 | header = 
 | image1 = Wells - Pennyless Porch.JPG
 | width1 = 240
 | alt1 =
 | caption1 = From the Market Place, Penniless Porch (left) leads  to Cathedral Green, and [[The Bishop's Eye, Wells|The Bishop's Eye]] (right) to the Bishop's Palace.
 | image2 = Wells Cathedral and Bishop's Palace - geograph.org.uk - 1671700.jpg
 | width2 = 213
 | alt2 =
 | caption2 = The cathdral seen beyond the wall and moat of the Bishop's Palace
 | image3=Wells Cathedral in the reflecting pool in the grounds of the Bisops Palace 4.jpg
 |width3=240 
 |alt3= 
 |caption3=To the south and east of the cathedral is the Bishop's Garden and reflecting pool.
 | image4 = Vicars Close Wells Somerset.jpg
 | width4 = 213
 | alt4 =
 | caption4 = Vicars' Close extends to the north of the cathedral
 }}
The cathedral is situated adjacent to a large lawned area, Cathedral Green, which is approached by three ancient gateways, [[Brown's Gatehouse, Wells|Brown's Gatehouse]], [[Penniless Porch, Wells|Penniless Porch]] and Chain Gate.  On Cathedral Green is the 12th-century [[The Old Deanery, Wells|Old Deanery]], largely rebuilt in the late 15th century by Dean Gunthorpe and remodelled by Dean Bathurst in the late 17th century. It is no longer the residence of the dean, and instead serves as offices for the diocese.<ref name="IoE">{{cite web|url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=483309 |title= The Old Deanery, Wells|work=Images of England|publisher=English Heritage|accessdate=13 January 2009}}</ref>

To the south of the cathedral is the moated Bishop's Palace, begun around 1210 by Bishop Jocelin of Wells but dating mostly from the 1230s. In the 15th century Bishop Beckington added the north wing, which is now the bishop's residence.<ref name="ioe">{{cite web | title=The Bishop's Palace and Bishop's House | work=Images of England | publisher=English Heritage | url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=483259 | accessdate=10 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.picturesofengland.com/England/Somerset/Wells/Bishop's_Palace,_Wells |title=Pictures of Bishop's Palace, Wells |accessdate=10 November 2007 |work=Pictures of England }}</ref> It was restored and extended by Benjamin Ferrey between 1846 and 1854.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bishop's Palace and Bishop's House |url=http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1382873|work=National Heritage list for England|publisher=English Heritage|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>

To the north of the cathedral and connected to it by the Chain Gate is Vicars' Close, a street planned in the 14th century and claimed to be the oldest purely residential street in Europe with all but one of its original buildings surviving intact.{{sfn|Leete-Hodge|1985|p=20}}{{sfn|Leete-Hodge|1985|p=29}} Buildings in Vicars' Close include the Vicars Hall and gateway at the south end, and the Vicars Chapel and Library at the north end.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Vicars' Chapel|url=http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1383201|work=National Heritage List for England|publisher=English Heritage|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Vicars' Hall including number 28, Vicars' Close|url=http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1383202|work=National Heritage List for England|publisher=English Heritage|accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref>

==In the arts and popular culture==
[[File:West Front of Wells Cathedral c.1795.jpg|thumb|upright= 1.25|West front as painted by [[J. M. W. Turner]] around 1795, watercolour on paper]]

British painter [[J. M. W. Turner]] visited Wells in 1795, making sketches of the precinct and a watercolour of the west front, now in the [[Tate Britain|Tate]] gallery.<ref>{{cite web|last=Turner|first=J.M.W.|authorlink=J. M. W. Turner|title=West Front of Wells Cathedral c.1795|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/turner-west-front-of-wells-cathedral-tw0782|publisher=Tate Gallery|accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref> Other artists whose paintings of the cathedral are in national collections are [[Albert Goodwin (artist)|Albert Goodwin]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Wells Cathedral|url=http://www.bridgemanart.com/de/asset/17117/Goodwin-Albert-1845-1932/Wells-Cathedral|publisher=Bridgeman|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> [[John Syer]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Wells Cathedral, Somerset|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/wells-cathedral-somerset-62060|work=Your paintings|publisher=BBC|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref> and [[Ken Howard (artist)|Ken Howard]].<ref>{{cite web|title=West Front of Wells Cathedral|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/west-front-of-wells-cathedral-41320|work=Your paintings|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref>

The cathedral was used as an inspiration for [[Ken Follett]]'s novel ''[[The Pillars of the Earth]]'' and, with a heavily modified central tower, featured as the completed fictional Kingsbridge Cathedral at the end of the 2010 television adaptation of that novel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ken-follett.com/bibliography/the_pillars_of_the_earth/kingsbridge.html |title=Kingsbridge: Real or fictional? | publisher=Ken Follett |accessdate=3 February 2013 }}</ref>

